The diagonals of a rectangle are equal in length, so the distance between $(5,3)$ and $(6,8)$ is the same as the distance between $(7,4)$ and $(x,y)$.  Using the distance formula, we have \[\sqrt{(6-5)^2+(8-3)^2}=\sqrt{(x-7)^2+(y-4)^2}.\]Squaring both sides, we get \[1+25=(x-7)^2+(y-4)^2.\]We also know that the diagonals of a rectangle bisect each other, so the midpoint of the diagonal between $(5,3)$ and $(6,8)$ is the same as the midpoint of the diagonal between $(7,4)$ and $(x,y)$.  The midpoint of the first diagonal is $\left(\frac{5+6}{2},\frac{3+8}{2}\right)=(5.5,5.5)$.  The midpoint of the second diagonal is $\left(\frac{7+x}{2},\frac{4+y}{2}\right)$.  Setting these equal, we get \[\frac{7+x}{2}=5.5\quad\text{and}\quad\frac{4+y}{2}=5.5.\]Solving, we find $x=8$ and $y=7$.  Therefore, $x+y=\boxed{15}$.

We have $z^5 = 1,$ so $z^5 - 1 = 0.$ Factoring, we get
\[(z - 1)(z^4 + z^3 + z^2 + z + 1) = 0.\]Since $z \neq 1,$ $z^4 + z^3 + z^2 + z + 1 = 0.$ Multiplying both sides by $z - 1,$ we get
\[z^5 - 1 = (z - 1)(z^4 + z^3 + z^2 + z + 1) = 0.\]Then
\begin{align*}
z + \frac{1}{z} + z^2 + \frac{1}{z^2} &= \frac{z^2 + 1}{z} + \frac{z^4 + 1}{z^2} \\
&= \frac{z^2 + 1 + z^4 + 1}{z} \\
&= \frac{z^4 + z^2 + 2}{z} \\
&= \frac{-(z + 1)}{z} \\
&= \frac{-z - 1}{z} \\
&= \frac{-z}{z} - \frac{1}{z} \\
&= -1 - \frac{1}{z}.
\end{align*}Multiplying both sides of $z^4 + z^3 + z^2 + z + 1 = 0$ by $z,$ we get
\[z^5 + z^4 + z^3 + z^2 + z = 0.\]Then
\begin{align*}
z + \frac{1}{z} + z^2 + \frac{1}{z^2} &= -z^4 - z^3 - z^2 \\
&= -z^4 - z^3 - z^2 - z - 1 + 1 \\
&= - (z^4 + z^3 + z^2 + z + 1) + 1 \\
&= -0 + 1 \\
&= \boxed{1}.
\end{align*}

Let $a$ be the number of apples, $o$ be the number of oranges, and $b$ be the number of bananas. We have the equations $a+o+b=100$ and $3a+2o+b=100$. Subtracting the first equation from the second, we get $2a+o=0$, so $o=-2a$. Substituting this into the first equation, we get $a-2a+b=100$, so $b=100+a$. Since $a$, $o$, and $b$ are all nonnegative integers, the only possible value of $a$ is $\boxed{50}$.

We can find $a$ and $b$ by comparing the coefficients of the terms in the product of the two polynomials.  The coefficient of $t^2$ in the product is $3t^2\cdot(-2)+4t^2\cdot a=12t^4+26t^3-8t^2-16t+6$.  The coefficient of $t^2$ in the right-hand side is $-6+4a$.  Therefore, $-6+4a=-8$, so $a=-.5$.  The coefficient of $t$ in the product is $3t^2\cdot b+5t\cdot(-2)=12t^4+26t^3-8t^2-16t+6$.  The coefficient of $t$ in the right-hand side is $-10$.  Therefore, $3b-10=-16$, so $b=-2$. The standard form of an ellipse is $\frac{x^2}{a^2} + \frac{y^2}{b^2} = 1$, where $a$ and $b$ are the semi-major and semi-minor axes, respectively. &= \frac{\sin^2 40^\circ + \cos^2 20^\circ}{\cos^2 10^\circ \sin^2 20^\circ \sin^2 40^\circ} \\
&= \frac{1 - \cos^2 40^\circ + \cos^2 20^\circ}{\cos^2 10^\circ \sin^2 20^\circ \sin^2 40^\circ} \\
&= \frac{1 + \cos^2 20^\circ - \sin^2 20^\circ}{\cos^2 10^\circ \sin^2 20^\circ \sin^2 40^\circ} \\

\[\cos 40^\circ = 1 - 2 \sin^2 20^\circ,\]so
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{\cos^2 10^\circ} + \frac{1}{\sin^2 20^\circ} + \frac{1}{\sin^2 40^\circ} &= \frac{2 - 2 \sin^2 20^\circ}{\cos^2 10^\circ \sin^2 20^\circ \sin^2 40^\circ} \\
&= \frac{2 \cos^2 20^\circ}{\cos^2 10^\circ \sin^2 20^\circ \sin^2 40^\circ} \\
&= \frac{2 \cos^2 20^\circ}{\cos^2 10^\circ \sin^2 20^\circ (1 - \cos^2 40^\circ)} \\
&= \frac{2 \cos^2 20^\circ}{\cos^2 10^\circ \sin^2 20^\circ \cos^2 40^\circ} \\
&= \frac{2}{\cos^2 10^\circ \sin^2 20^\circ}.
\end{align*}From the double angle formula,
\[\sin 20^\circ = 2 \sin 10^\circ \cos 10^\circ,\]so
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{\cos^2 10^\circ} + \frac{1}{\sin^2 20^\circ} + \frac{1}{\sin^2 40^\circ} &= \frac{2}{\cos^2 10^\circ (2 \sin 10^\circ \cos 10^\circ)^2} \\
&= \frac{1}{2 \sin^2 10^\circ \cos^4 10^\circ} \\
&= \frac{1}{2 \sin^2 10^\circ (1 - \sin^2 10^\circ)} \\
&= \frac{1}{2 \sin^2 10^\circ - 2 \sin^4 10^\circ}.
\end{align*}From the triple angle formula,
\[\sin 30^\circ = 3 \sin 10^\circ - 4 \sin^3 10^\circ,\]so
\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{\cos^2 10^\circ} + \frac{1}{\sin^2 20^\circ} + \frac{1}{\sin^2 40^\circ} &= \frac{1}{2 \sin 10^\circ - 2 \sin^3 10^\circ} \\
&= \frac{1}{2 \sin 10^\circ (1 - \sin^2 10^\circ)} \\
&= \frac{1}{2 \sin 10^\circ \cos^2 10^\circ} \\
&= \frac{1}{2 \sin 10^\circ (1 - \sin^2 10^\circ)} \\
&= \frac{1}{2 \sin 10^\circ - 2 \sin^3 10^\circ} \\

$\omega^3 = 1$ என்பது $\omega^3 - 1 = 0$ என்பதை எழுதலாம்.  இதன் மீջ்தியாக $\omega^3 - 1 = (\omega - 1)(\omega^2 + \omega + 1) = 0$ என்பதை எழுதலாம்.  இந்த மீջ்தியில் $\omega \neq 1$ என்பதை எழுதலாம்.  இந்த மீջ்தியின் மீջ்தியாக $\omega^2 + \omega + 1 = 0$ என்பதை எழுதலாம்.  இதன் மீջ்தியாக $\omega^2 + \omega = -1$ என்பதை எழுதலாம்.  இதன் மீջ்தியாக $\frac{1}{\omega + 1} = \frac{1}{-\omega^2} = -\omega^2$ என்பதை எழுதலாம்.  இதன் மீջ்தியாக $\frac{1}{1 + \omega^2} = \frac{1}{-\omega}$ என்பதை எழுதலாம்.  இதன் மீջ்தியாக $\frac{1}{1 + \omega} + \frac{1}{1 + \omega^2} = -\omega^2 - \frac{1}{\omega} = -\omega^2 - \omega = \boxed{1}.$

We use the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABC$ to find $\cos \angle ACB$:
\begin{align*}
AB^2 &= AC^2 + BC^2 - 2 \cdot AC \cdot BC \cdot \cos \angle ACB \\
\Rightarrow \qquad 5^2 &= 6^2 + 6^2 - 2 \cdot 6 \cdot 6 \cdot \cos \angle ACB \\
\Rightarrow \qquad \cos \angle ACB &= \frac{6^2 + 6^2 - 5^2}{2 \cdot 6 \cdot 6} = \frac{35}{72}.
\end{align*}Now, we use the Law of Cosines on triangle $ACD$ to find $AD$:
\begin{align*}
AD^2 &= AC^2 + CD^2 - 2 \cdot AC \cdot CD \cdot \cos \angle ACD \\
&= 6^2 + 4^2 - 2 \cdot 6 \cdot 4 \cdot \frac{35}{72} \\
&= 36 + 16 - \frac{70}{3} \\
&= \frac{100}{3}.
\end{align*}Therefore, $AD = \boxed{\frac{10}{\sqrt{3}}}$.
